## 12. Git Workflow & Branching

### Branch Strategy: Git Flow (adapted)

```
main           production-ready code only. Tagged with version releases.
develop        integration branch. All features merge here first.
feature/*      individual feature work (e.g. feature/dynamic-fields)
fix/*          bug fixes (e.g. fix/socket-reconnect)
hotfix/*       urgent fixes on main (e.g. hotfix/login-crash)
release/*      release preparation (e.g. release/1.2.0)
docs/*         documentation-only changes
```

### Conventional Commits (mandatory)

All commit messages must follow this format:

```
<type>(<scope>): <short description>

[optional body]

[optional footer]
```

**Types:**

| Type | When to use |
|---|---|
| `feat` | New feature |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `docs` | Documentation only |
| `style` | Formatting, no logic change |
| `refactor` | Code restructure, no feature/fix |
| `test` | Adding or fixing tests |
| `chore` | Build tools, dependencies |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |

**Examples:**
```
feat(inventory): add real-time stock updates via Socket.IO
fix(auth): resolve JWT refresh token race condition
feat(products): implement dynamic field builder with drag-and-drop
test(api): add integration tests for stock movement endpoint
docs(readme): add docker deployment instructions
chore(deps): upgrade prisma to v5.10
```

### Commit Rules

- Small, atomic commits  one logical change per commit
- Never commit directly to `main` or `develop`
- Every feature/fix lives in its own branch
- PRs must reference the issue they close (`Closes #42`)
- Commit messages in present tense, imperative mood ("add" not "added")

